05053nam a22009255i 9780813564784DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20162016nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2015035675  a97808135647847 a10.36019/97808135647842doi  a(DE-B1597)526181  a(OCoLC)951678578  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aD804.45.U55bL57 2016 4aD804.45.U55bL57 2016 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a940.53/182231 aLipstadt, Deborah E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHolocaust :bAn American Understanding /cDeborah E. Lipstadt. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (220 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKey Words in Jewish Studies ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Terms of Debate -- t2. State of the Question -- t3. In a New Key -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aImmediately after World War II, there was little discussion of the Holocaust, but today the word has grown into a potent political and moral symbol, recognized by all. In Holocaust: An American Understanding, renowned historian Deborah E. Lipstadt explores this striking evolution in Holocaust consciousness, revealing how a broad array of Americans—from students in middle schools to presidents of the United States—tried to make sense of this inexplicable disaster, and how they came to use the Holocaust as a lens to interpret their own history. Lipstadt weaves a powerful narrative that touches on events as varied as the civil rights movement, Vietnam, Stonewall, and the women’s movement, as well as controversies over Bitburg, the Rwandan genocide, and the bombing of Kosovo. Drawing upon extensive research on politics, popular culture, student protests, religious debates and various strains of Zionist ideologies, Lipstadt traces how the Holocaust became integral to the fabric of American life. Even popular culture, including such films as Dr. Strangelove and such books as John Hershey’s The Wall, was influenced by and in turn influenced thinking about the Holocaust. Equally important, the book shows how Americans used the Holocaust to make sense of what was happening in the United States. Many Americans saw the civil rights movement in light of Nazi oppression, for example, while others feared that American soldiers in Vietnam were destroying a people identified by the government as the enemy. Lipstadt demonstrates that the Holocaust became not just a tragedy to be understood but also a tool for interpreting America and its place in the world. Ultimately Holocaust: An American Understanding tells us as much about America in the years since the end of World War II as it does about the Holocaust itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xForeign public opinion, American. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xHistoriography. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aauschwitz.  aconcentration camp.  adachau.  adeath camp.  agenocide.  ahimler.  ahitler.  aholocaust.  anazi.  asobibor.  atreblinka.  aworld war 2.  aworld war two.  aww2.  awwii.  azion.  azionism.  azionist.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066614440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356478440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813564784423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813564784/original  a978-3-11-066614-4  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS 